Among the protesters were supporters of Friends of the Earth Network, Extinction Rebellion, Our Future Leeds and Just Transition Wakefield were all present. Mayor Tracy Brabin, who belongs to the Labour Party, addressed the crowd. [size=thousands]

On 6 November 2021, climate activists marched through Norwich to protest demanding leaders gathered at the COP26 climate conference in Glasgow to take drastic action to counter climate change. The event was organised by the COP26 Coalition. Amongst the protesters were supporters of Extinction Rebellion, Norwich Friends of the Earth and the Norfolk Campaign Against Climate Change. [size=no report]

On 4 November 2021, environmental campaigners, including Extinction Rebellion, CND Scotland, and Faslane Peace Camp activists, marched through the south side of Glasgow amid the COP26 summit. They rallied outside a Home Office building in Cessnock and the BAE Systems facility to protest against military companies profiting from climate change. Earlier in the day, members from No Coal Japan dressed as Japanese anime characters gathered opposite the COP26 conference venue, demanding Japan end its support for coal power. Ocean Rebellion activists wearing giant fish heads protested against bottom-trawling fishing, claiming it released harmful substances in the sea. [size=no report]

On 3 November 2021, almost 100 people gathered at City Park in Bradford, calling for action on climate change at the climate conference COP26. They chanted, 'Actions speak, talk is cheap.' Members belonging to Global Justice, Bingley Christian Aid group, Extinction Rebellion, and a Green Party councilor joined the event. [size=almost 100]

On 22 October 2021, Youth Strike for Climate campaigners marched through Bristol to mobilize people for action on climate ahead of the COP26 summit taking place in Glasgow from 31 October 2021. The event was co-organized by some university student unions and Extinction Rebellion members. [size=no report]

On 28 September 2021, taxi drivers representing the App Drivers' and Couriers' Union gathered outside Uber offices in Bristol as part of a 24-hour strike in protest over poor pay, conditions and unfair dismissals. Drivers demanded that rates be set at 2 GBP per mile. This was part of a series of co-ordinated strikes by members of the union across several cities in the country. In attendance was a sitting councillor for the Green Party. [size=no report]

On 24 September 2021, climate protesters marched and rallied outside Scottish Parliament in Edinburgh as part of the Fridays for Future campaign, demanding the abandonment of fossil fuels and government action over the climate crisis. A West Scotland Green MSP also attended the rally. [size=no report]

On 24 September 2021, over 200 climate strikers, including members of the Extinction Rebellion, gathered in Parliament Square and marched around London - Westminster as part of the Fridays for Future campaign, demanding the abandonment of fossil fuels and government action over the climate crisis. A Labour MP, Green Party member (a former leader), and Labour member (former leader) gave speeches to the crowd. [size=over 200]

actor2: Police Forces of the United Kingdom (2010-)
notes: On 25 August 2021, Extinction Rebellion activists protested at Oxford Circus, the Department for International Trade, and Brazilian Embassy in London - Westminster to continue their two-week Impossible Rebellion campaign to lobby the government to halt investment in fossil fuels. More than 40 women and FINT (female, intersex, nonbinary, trans) members of the Extinction Rebellion set up a pink sculpture and demonstration at Oxford Circus, where police arrested 6 people for various offenses. Earlier in the day, activists from Money Rebellion, an offshoot of Extinction Rebellion, gathered at the Department for International Trade to hold a mock awards ceremony where a 'Charred Earth' award was given to the department. Members of Extinction Rebellion, Amazon Rebellion, Brazil Matters, CAFOD, Greenpeace, Parents for Future (associated with Fridays for Future), and Survival International gathered at the Embassy of Brazil to show solidarity with indigenous people in the Amazon Rainforest. [size=more than 40]

On 21 August 2021, hundreds of people gathered at the gates of a museum in Hoxton in London - Hackney, calling to remove the Geffrye statue, a controversial slave-trader statue. Participants included Stand Up to Racism campaigners, Labour MP for Hackney North and Stoke Newington, Green party members, and representatives of the Kurdish and Turkish community group Day-Mer. [size=hundreds]

On 15 August 2021, animal welfare activists belonging to Oxford Vegan Action gathered on Cornwall Street in Oxford to demand that the Oxford Greyhound Stadium, a venue that hosts greyhound racing, is not allowed to reopen in March 2022 as planned. Activists denounced the practice as 'cruel'. Sitting councillors belonging to the Labour and Green parties were also present. [size=no report]

On 22 July 2021, Extinction Rebellion members, including Doctors for Extinction Rebellion members, staged a noisy march in Weston-super-Mare as the third demonstration this week to protest against Third Bristol Airport expansion plans. Earlier in the day, Bristol Youth Strike 4 Climate members also demonstrated outside the town hall to object to the proposed expansion of Bristol Airport. [size=no report]

On 1 May 2021, between 100 to 200 anti-government protesters including members of Unite, Unison and Extinction Rebellion marched through Bristol in a show of opposition to the Police, Crime, Sentencing and Courts Bill, which proposes to give police more powers to shut down peaceful protests. [size=between 100 to 200]

On 3 April 2021, hundreds of anti-government protesters, including supporters of the Socialist Workers' Party, Black Lives Matter, Stand Up To Racism and Extinction Rebellion, gathered in Oxford to oppose to the Police, Crime, Sentencing and Courts Bill which aims to give police more powers to shutdown peaceful protests. [size=hundreds]

On 3 April 2021, more than 1000 anti-government protesters, including supporters of the Socialist Worker's Party, Extinction Rebellion, Black Lives Matter and Stand Up To Racism gathered in central Sheffield to oppose the Police, Crime, Sentencing and Courts Bill which aims to give police more powers to shutdown peaceful protests. [size=more than 1000]

On 3 April 2021, anti-government protesters, including supporters of the Socialist Worker's Party, Extinction Rebellion, Black Lives Matter, Let's Stop Aquind and trade unions gathered in the Guildhall Square in Portsmouth to oppose the Police, Crime, Sentencing and Courts Bill which aims to give police more powers to shutdown peaceful protests. Protesters heard speeches from spokespersons from various groups and one protesters, dress as the grim reaper, carries a coffin with the words 'Democracy' written on the side. [size=no report]

On 1 February 2021, Palestine Action and Extinction Rebellion activists staged a protest at a factory in Oldham that produces parts for drones believed to be used in the killings of Palestine civilians by the Israeli military. Protesters climbed onto the roof of the factory and scattered red paint over the windows and doors of the factory. They also sprayed the phrase 'Shut Elbit Down' over the entrance. Police were present at the scene but there was no report of police intervention. [size=no report]

On 11 December 2020, members of Extinction Rebellion, Greenpeace and other environmental campaigners staged a protest in front of Bath Abbey in Bath to support the Fridays for Future #Fightfor1point5 campaign. They called for actions from MPs to keep climate heating under 1.5 degrees. [size=no report]

source: The Northern Echo; South West Farmer
notes: On 25 September 2020, campaign group Save British Farming held a tractor demonstration in Northallerton against post-Brexit trade deals that could open the door for American imported food with lower standards than British produce. A member of Green Party also attended the rally. [size=no report]

On 25 September 2020, students and supporters of Extinction Rebellion gathered at Broadgate in Coventry as a part of the Youth Strike 4 Climate movement's Global Climate Day of Action, demanding action on the climate crisis. [size=no report]

On 25 September 2020, members of UK Student Climate Network marched through Oxford as part of ongoing climate protests. They dropped banners in places, including outside the city council offices in St Aldates, the Radcliffe Camera, the Westgate Centre, and the Plain. Campaigners from Parents For Future Oxford also placed dozens of pairs of shoes in front of the Radcliffe Camera to represent all the children who will be affected by climate change. [size=no report]

On 29 August 2020, activists from Make Votes Matter staged a rally on the High Street in Stroud to demand proportional representation for House of Commons elections. Members from the Labour Party, Green Party and Liberal Democrats gave speeches to the participants. [size=no report]
On 13 March 2020, a 'handful' of protesters appeared for the Youth Climate Strike at Lemon Quay in Truro, Cornwall, as a part of Fridays for Future. [size=a handful]

On 14 February 2020, young activists protested about the climate emergency outside of the County Hall in Tenby, Wales, as part of the Fridays For Future climate strikes. Extinction Rebellion also supported the event. [size=no report]

On 14 February 2020, students and members of Extinction Rebellion staged a 'die-in' and then marched through Bradford as a part of the Youth Strike 4 Climate Protest demanding action on the climate emergency. [size=no report]

On 25 June 2022, hundreds of rail workers represented by the RMT Union and their supporters marched through Bristol as part of strike action after failing to agree to pay and working conditions proposals. Workers were joined by representatives from Extinction Rebellion, ACORN Union, Unison and the People's Assembly. [size=hundreds]

On 23 April 2022, cyclists gathered outside the Scottish Parliament in Edinburgh to call on the government to improve infrastructure for cyclists as well as slower speed limits near homes and workplaces. This protest was part of the Pedal on Parliament campaign. Sitting MSPs belonging to the Green Party, SNP, Conservatives and Labour were all present and spoke at the protest. [size=no report]

On 22 March 2022, Imperial College staff gathered in London - Kensington and Chelsea at the call of UCU to demonstrate against pension cuts, deteriorating pay, and poor working conditions. Green Party representatives took part in the demonstration. [size=no report]

source: The Northern Echo; Twitter; BBC News
notes: On 22 March 2022, 60 Durham University staff and students staged a picket in Durham (County Durham, England) at the call of UCU to demonstrate against pension cuts, deteriorating pay, and poor working conditions. The co-leader of the Green Party took part in the demonstration. [size=60]

On 29 January 2022, between 250 and 300 local residents and environmentalists gathered in Ringland to protest against the Norwich Western Link road development. Members of Extinction Rebellion, Friends of the Earth and a sitting Green Party councillor were present along with well-known TV naturalist Chris Packer. [size=between 250 and 300]

On 18 December 2021, anti-racism campaigners gathered outside the Town Hall in Sheffield to protest against the government's Nationality and Borders bill which is currently being debated in parliament. Members of Sheffield Trade Union Council (TUC), Sheffield Say No To Racism, Stand Up To Racism, Extinction Rebellion, Green and Labour Party councillors, and Sheffield Hallam MP Olivia Blake attended the protest. [size=no report]

Around 12 December 2021, climate activists gathered outside Hampshire County Council in Winchester to protest against the council pension fund's investments in fossil fuel industries. The protest was led by Unison with Extinction Rebellion Winchester, WINACC, Winchester Green Party, and other local organizations. [size=no report]

On 6 November 2021, thousands of climate activists marched through central Leeds before gathering in Millennium Square to protest demanding leaders gathered at the COP26 climate conference in Glasgow to take drastic action to counter climate change. This event was organised by the COP26 Coalition. Among the protesters were supporters of Friends of the Earth Network, Extinction Rebellion, Our Future Leeds and Just Transition Wakefield were all present. Mayor Tracy Brabin, who belongs to the Labour Party, addressed the crowd. [size=thousands]

On 5 November 2021, around 200 people led by the Tayside COP26 Coalition marched through Dundee to demand actions to tackle climate change. Members from Extinction Rebellion, Dundee University, Friends of the Earth, and dozens of schoolchildren joined the march. [size=around 200]

On 1 November 2021, climate activists belonging to the newly formed Tayside COP26 Coalition, which includes Extinction Rebellion, Friends of the Earth, Bioregioning Tayside and trade unions gathered in Dundee to stage a demonstration demanding 'climate justice' and the release of Extinction Rebellion climate activist, James Brown, who is currently incarcerated in Wandsworth Prison for his participation in a demonstration in which he glued himself to an aeroplane at London City Airport. [size=no report]

On 20 October 2021, 12 climate campaigners from Spain marched through Darlington to highlight the climate crisis as part of their journey to march to Glasgow in time for COP26 on 1 November. Friends of the Earth organized a rally, and it was joined by the mayor of Darlington and councilors from the Labour Party and Green Party. [size=at least 15]

On 2 October 2021, union representatives and residents gathered in central Lancaster to protest against proposed cuts to Universal Credit of twenty pounds per week. In attendance were local councilors belonging to the Labour and Green parties as well as representatives of the RMT union, Bakers and the Food and Allied Workers Union. [size=no report]

On 24 July 2021, members of the ACORN Union marched through Oxford to the offices of local estate agents Penny and Sinclair to protest against policies that the agents allegedly employed which exclude potential renters who sought to use housing benefit schemes to fund their rent payments. Also in attendance was a sitting Labour Party MP and Green Party councillors. [size=no report]

On 13 July 2021, members of Unite the Union representing the University of Glasgow catering staff gathered outside the university in Glasgow to protest against the University's use of 'fire and rehire' tactics. In attendance were sitting members of the Scottish Parliament belonging to the Labour and Green parties. [size=no report]

On 5 June 2021, around 600 people marched through London - Newham in a show of opposition to local government plans to build the Silvertown Tunnel which will connect Greenwich to Newham Silvertown. Protesters highlighted the potential negative environmental effects of such a development such as increased air pollution. Representatives from the Green Party and Labour Party were in attendance as well as supporters of Stand Up To Racism, Choked Up and Extinction Rebellion. This event was organized by Stop the Silvertown Tunnel Coalition. [size=around 600]

On 12 February 2022, local supporters of the Save Winney Hill campaign gathered in Shrewsbury to protest against plans for a housing development and nursing home in the area. Members of the Liberal Democratic, Labour, Conservative and Green Parties were present including sitting councillors. [size=no report]

On 1 December 2021, more than 1,000 university staff, students, and University and College Union members rallied and marched in Bristol as part of a three-day strike action to protest pay, pensions and working conditions. A Labour Metro Mayor and a Deputy Green Party leader (who is also a councilor) also joined the event. [size=more than 1,000]

On 6 November 2021, thousands of climate activists marched through central Leeds before gathering in Millennium Square to protest demanding leaders gathered at the COP26 climate conference in Glasgow to take drastic action to counter climate change. Mayor Tracy Brabin, who belongs to the Labour Party, addressed the crowd. [size=thousands]

On 4 November 2021, dozens of environmental campaigners, using a bamboo structure, blocked the entrance of the Three Counties Showground in Malvern to protest the site hosting the Three Counties Defence and Security Expo, citing the impact of the military sector on people and the planet. The protesters blocked people from entering the site, causing traffic chaos at the gate. Participating groups included Peace Pledge Union, Pax Christi, Stop the War Coalition, Coventry Justice and Peace, Coventry Friends of Palestine, Hereford Peace Council, Malvern Individuals for Peace, Extinction Rebellion Malvern, Extinction Rebellion Peace, Quakers, Hereford Palestinian Solidarity Campaign, Three Counties Campaign Against Arms Trade, and Stroud Red Band. [size=dozens]

A Labour MP, Green Party member (a former leader), and Labour member (former leader) gave speeches to the crowd. [size=over 200]

On 1 October 2022, dozens of supporters of the Enough is Enough (EiE) campaign gathered outside the town council offices in Falmouth for a political rally to highlight the cost of living crisis and demand support from the government. Tamsyn Widdon, Green Party Cornwall councilor spoke to the crowd. Striking members of RMT, CWU, and ACORN joined the protestors. The rally was part of a national day of protest and was supported by trade unions and community organizations. [size=dozens]

On 1 October 2022, hundreds of supporters of the Enough is Enough (EiE) campaign marched through Brighton for a political rally to highlight the cost of living crisis and demand support from the government. Striking RMT, CWU, ACORN, Unite the Union and Unison members joined protesters. Climate activist group Extinction Rebellion also joined the protestors while Labour MP for Brighton Kemptown Lloyd Russell-Moyle spoke to the crowd. The rally was part of a national day of protest and was supported by trade unions and community organizations. [size=hundreds]

On 25 June 2022, trade union representatives and their supporters marched through Cambridge in support of strike action by the RMT Union after failing to agree to pay and working conditions proposals. Workers were joined by representatives from People's Assembly Against Austerity, Extinction Rebellion and National Education Union. [size=no report]

On 1 May 2022, 200 people gathered in Lancaster to protest against the cost of living crisis. Green Party, UCU, NEU, RMT, Blackpool, Fylde and Wyre Trades Union Council, Extinction Rebellion, Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament, Tenants and Community Union, East Meets West, Stand Up to Racism, and Out in The Bay took part in the demonstration. [size=200]

On 20 January 2020, hundreds of people joined the protest organised by Safe Passage in Parliament Square in London - Westminster to ensure the rights of unaccompanied child refugees to be reunited with their families in the UK post-Brexit. A number of MPs, SNP, Labour Party, Liberal Democrats and Green Party members joined the rally. [size=hundreds]

notes: On 12 November 2021, on the final morning of the COP26 summit, COP26 Coalition leading hundreds of global civil society representatives, including representatives of farmers, Indigenous people, women, academics, trade unions, and environmental NGOs, walked out of the convention centre in Glasgow to join Oxfam's 'Ineffective Fire-Fighting World Leaders' protesting outside. Participants included activists from the Tla'amin Nation (part of Coast Salish Indigenous people in Canada), Chile, Brazil, and members from Ringo, Friends of the Earth, Fridays for Future and the Extinction Rebellion. Police arrested two people after they tried to scale the fence outside the venue. [size=hundreds]

[size=around 300]
